04_translate_point


  1. Question

    A p1 wallpaper was made by using repeated translations. I have depicted the translation of point \((-0.2, -0.69)\) in the direction \(\theta=0.28\) (radians) by a distance of \(r=2.3\).


    What are the coordinates of the point at the end of the arrow (the result of the translation)?

    • The horizontal coordinate, \(x'=\)
    • The vertical coordinate, \(y'=\)

    Solution

    To find the changes of translation, we can use trigonometry.

    \[\Delta x = r\cdot \cos(\theta)\] \[\Delta y = r\cdot \sin(\theta)\]

    Let’s evaluate those changes.

    \[\Delta x ~=~ (2.3)\cos(0.28) ~=~ 2.21\] \[\Delta y ~=~ (2.3)\sin(0.28) ~=~ 0.64\]

    We can then add these changes to the original point.

    \[x' ~=~ -0.2+2.21 ~=~ 2.01\] \[y' ~=~ -0.69+0.64 ~=~ -0.05\]



    Solution

    To find the changes of translation, we can use trigonometry.

    \[\Delta x = r\cdot \cos(\theta)\] \[\Delta y = r\cdot \sin(\theta)\]

    Let’s evaluate those changes.

    \[\Delta x ~=~ (2.3)\cos(0.28) ~=~ 2.21\] \[\Delta y ~=~ (2.3)\sin(0.28) ~=~ 0.64\]

    We can then add these changes to the original point.
